'''Jiří Grossmann''' ([[20 July]] [[1941]]  &ndash; [[5 December]] [[1971]]) was a [[Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak]] theatre [[actor]], [[poet]], and [[composer]]. 

==Life==
Grossmann was born in [[Prague]]. After his graduation he started at the technical university [[ČVUT]], but left in 1962 when he met [[Miloslav Šimek]] in the Olympik bar. Grossmann performed with Dixie Party Band in the Olympik bar, playing on contrabass also. They immediately established a theatre double and started writing poems, short-stories and stageplays. Their first theatre group was called [[Mlok]].<ref name="mlok">[http://www.radio.cz/cz/clanek/5499 Czech Radio Broadcast Article]</ref> Grossmann and Šimek's most famous project was '''Navštěvní dny''', a theatre-styled show performed in theatre [[Semafor]].<ref name="havlikova">Nevyjasněná úmrtí V. 1st Ed. Praha: The World Circle Foundation, 2000  ISBN 80-902731-7-3</ref>

[[Image:Návštěvní dny.jpg|left|thumb|350px|[[Miloslav Šimek]] with Jiří Grossmann in Návštěvní dny]]

The duo was persecuted after the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] occupation of [[Czechoslovakia]] in 1968 following the [[Prague Spring]].

When Grossmann realized he was dying of [[Hodgkin's lymphoma]], he wrote one of his most sad lyrics called "[http://zpevnik.100plus.cz/texty/z-texty/zavidim.htm Závidím (I Yellow)]"<ref name="havlikova">Nevyjasněná úmrtí V. 1st Ed. Praha: The World Circle Foundation, 2000  ISBN 80-902731-7-3</ref> expressing fairs of life. A few days before Christmas in 1971, Grossmann died in the hospital.

The Jiří Grossmann Theatre<ref name="theatre">[http://www.muzikus.cz/kluby/divadlo-jiriho-grossmanna~1091/ Jiří Grossmann Theatre]</ref> and Prague's Jiří Grossmann's Archway commemorate him today.

